solution.p:
When finding the coefficients of a Taylor polynomial, it is often helpful to not combine into a single number products such as (-3)(-2)(-1) and (-4)(-3)(-2)(-1) in order to better observe patterns; indeed, by not combining the constants that arise in higher derivatives of f(x) = \ln(1+x), we see a pattern of alternating signs, as well as factorials that arise.  From the right column of Table and the fact that c_k = \frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}, we see that





      c_0 = 0






      c_1 = 1






      c_2 = \frac{-1}{2!} = -\frac{1}{2}






      c_3 = \frac{(-2)(-1)}{3!} = \frac{1}{3}






      c_4 = \frac{(-3)(-2)(-1)}{4!} = -\frac{1}{4}






      c_5 = \frac{(-4)(-3)(-2)(-1)}{5!} = \frac{1}{5}



so that the degree 5 Taylor approximation of f(x) = \ln(1+x) at a = 0 is

  T_5(x) = 1x - \frac{1}{2}x^2 + \frac{1}{3}x^3 - \frac{1}{4}x^4 + \frac{1}{5}x^5.
